Notes:

It an easy print, just make sure your bed leveled so you can have a really nice first layer.

Making Grooves Depper

The model has a few grooves to provide details like cabin glass, ailerons etc. Using a sharp pointy object like a scriber make this grooves deeper so they don't disappear when sanding.

Sanding

Frist sand the model using 80 paper, just be patient. Then use a 240 paper, and later a 500 paper.

Glue

I have used super glue (cyanoacrylate) to put the model together, it work great on ABS.

Painting

I have used white acrylic paint on my models, about 5 or 6 layer. Again, just be patient and you will have an absolutely great looking model.

title: Zoe-trope using a Maltese cross (Geneva wheel)

description.text:
https://youtu.be/zJ4dq0jks5g
This Zoe-trope uses one of the oldest mechanical solutions for the movie industry, the Maltese cross, also referred to as the Geneva wheel. It was used in camera's and projectors, to rapidly move the celluloid from one picture to the next. Since we don't have our pictures on celluloid, we print them on a CD. Ten pictures per movie.
Every step, ten slightly different pictures rotate 36 degrees and give the impression of motion. If you don't want to draw pictures yourself, you can find plenty of them in the Internet. To get the right size, paste them in Word, click right and set the width at 12 cm.
The gear wheels were defined with the excellent and very simple to use gear wheel generator at http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:900277/#files
An interesting article on the Geneva wheel (Maltese cross) can be found at
http://kmoddl.library.cornell.edu/tutorials/10/

title: Anycubic Kossel BLTouch Fan Mount
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I have an updated version (sort of) for mounting the BL on the printer.
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2374473

This is a simple mount for the BLTouch on the Anycubic Kossel.

It places the BL at a height that is within the mounting range and does not interfere with the movement of the hot end.

Since your printer is probably different than mine, you should carefully and accurately set the offsets for you machine in the firmware. The X and Y offsets should be right about:
X = +36.1
Y = -27.2
My Z offset was: -2.1

Again, check and set the offsets for YOUR machine.

This will slightly impact distance on the +X and -Y side of the build plate. You may have to reduce your build size slightly. Be sure to set your probing range correctly or you may hit something.

Also, if you are using the original bed mounts, depending on how big your probing area, build area and model are, you may hit the front right bed mount (don't ask...). I originally removed this one mount to give me enough clearance. Please manually move the hotend a little at a time to verify clearances.

Having the BL has made things SO much easier. No more fiddling with the end stops, etc.

I am working on another version of this mount that should allow full range of motion on the hot end. I'll post that up when I finish it.

  1. Printed out frame (you may have to widen the screw holes).

  4. On the other side I used double sided mounting tape and taped the fan onto the frame, allows for easy removal when replacing the filter.
  5. Connected the red wires to one 12 “ red wire, solder then and then cover with electrical tape.
  6. Repeated step 5 using the Black wires.
  7. Connected the wires to the 12V line and GRN line at the power supply. This way when I turn on the printer, the fans automatically turn on.

description.text:
UPDATE 27/04/17 Build photos added.

UPDATE 18/04/17 Build photos added.

This thing is an offset bracket for mounting a 120mm 230v axial fan to an 80mm aluminium tube.

I have recently brought another small tabletop injection moulding machine,and am having issues with the heat travelling up the melting cylinder and prematurely pre-melting the plastic pellets prior to extrusion.

This results in the cylinder not extruding,and plastic pellets getting lodged in the cylinder.

This is an attempt to decrease to heat build up and prevent the heat travelling into the cold area non melt zone of the barrel.

i have decided to use the items i have got lying around the lab.( give them a go first ) ,-)

I shall eventually mill out a water jacket and use a peltier cooling block with external cooling fans.

Hopefully FOR NOW this forced air cooling will make a worthwhile temporary cooling solution,only my experiments / tests would confirm or dismiss.

The two fan setup will be working in a push/pull arrangement to force to cool air around the barrel and removing the excessive heat buildup

All metal 120mm server fans are to be used,this suits the industrial nature of my machine and are more powerful than their 12v counterparts.(also no psu is required)

I am in the process of printing and waiting for parts to arrive.
Tests will be carried out and photos/video of my finding posted shortly.

This design should help with the many small tabletop machine available today that suffer this particular problem of premature melting prior to extrusion.

On my machine the extrusion barrel measures 38mm,i will be drilling out the hole in the aluminium tube to 40mm to account for heat expansion and to allow for slight barrel movement.

120mm fan grill cover used in the design http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1595208/#files Thanks Kevin293

Enjoy ,-)

title: Anycubic Kossel Hotbed Glass Mounts
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I have updated the lower mount.

It now has a pin that fits the heat bed.

I used peaberry's hotbed mounts, but made these glass mounts.

Peaberry's bed mounts: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1982435

Because I'm running a BLTouch that hangs out a little, I wanted the holders for the glass on my hotbed to be as low as possible to avoid any chance of contact with the BL.

These fit below the hotbed, that is, not supporting it, gap around the hotbed and are flush with the top of the 3mm glass surface (except for the head of the bolt).

I printed both his mounts and these mounts in PLA to at least get me printing with heat, but if they show signs of softening with higher temps, I'll redo them the ABS or PETG.

You'll need to print 3 X of both parts.

The lower part mounts to the beams with 2 X 3mm bolts and T nuts. And the upper part is bolted using a 3mm bolt and nut.

You may need support for the nut cavity, is so, be sure to get it all out prior to inserting the nut. It's a blind hole, so only one way in and out.

Because of the tension towards the glass and the compression from the hold down bolt, I went heavy on everything. I used 4 bottoms, 4 tops and 6 perimeters @ .2 and 60% infill.

IMPORTANT! These mounts DO NOT clamp the glass down in any fashion. They only apply pressure to the edge of the glass. It's enough to hold the glass in place and keep it from moving or spinning during printing, but if you turn the machine up-side down, the glass may fall out. Also, since they don't clamp, be sure that your heat bed is actually as flat as possible, without any type of convex to it.

description.text:
This is a copy of a puzzle found on Puzzle Will Be Played. Its full English title is The Magic Flute - Queen of the Night as it is one of a series by Gregory Benedetti.
http://puzzlewillbeplayed.com/DieZauberfloete/KoeniginDerNacht/
The puzzle was constructed using Burr Tools and I have included the .xmpuzzle file so you can play with the pieces and export different sized STL files if you wish.

Print one of each piece.
Assemble the pieces into a 'panpipe' shape.
This is not as difficult as some of the other puzzles I have tried and looks really nice printed in different colours. I used the free samples I received from Faberdashery.
The pieces have a 0.15 mm tolerance to stop them from getting jammed. I chose this value mainly because I wanted to print the pieces at 0.15 mm layer height. I was really pleased with how smooth the surfaces are at this resolution.

Judging by the many postings of late, lots of folks are trying to make a cooling fan shroud or duct that will properly cool their prints, but aren't have a lot of success. I believe the reason for this is that all the designs are using axial fans. Axial fans are designed to produce a lot of flow at low back pressure. As soon as you add ducting, the back pressure reduces the flow rate rapidly and you get little, if any, cooling.
The right answer is to use a centrifugal fan. The duct I'm posting uses one, and believe me, it provides plenty of cooling air for your prints.

UPDATE: The FreeCAD files are now included in the archive. The fan itself is readily available on EBay for around $5US or so. Look for DC-2pin-12V-50mm-x-15mm-PC-Cooler-Cooling-Brushless-Blower-Fan-Hole-to-Hole-57mm. Look at the pictures to see how to attach it to the duct. You'll probably have to make your own mount to your X carriage. I provide an example and various length links to mount it. Again, look at the pictures.
Design files in FreeCAD are available. I will post them if there is interest.

comments.text: I had to laugh when I saw the title of your thing.  :-D As you say, there's lots of rubbish fan designs. title: GEEETech i3C (METAL version): Dual Extruder FAN & LED (V3 with Radial FAN)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
Hi,
now GEEETech proposes the Acrylic Prusa I3 pro series, B for single extruder and C for dual extruder, with metallic parts instead of original printer ones.
Quite immediately I’ve ordered the upgrade kit in order to improve the stability and the quality of my, already not-so-bad printer, unfortunately the customization I’ve designed for the plastic version of this printer cannot be used on the metal one, so I’ve started designing a completely new customization, starting with all lesson learned from my original customization!
One, main, lesson learned was to decouple all contact, in order to enable easy mounting, maintenance and upgrade!
Here the Dual Extruder FAN & LED component of my new customization in his third iteration…
… compared to previews V2 I’ve “just” completely redesign the cooling subsystem around brand new Radial Fan, with a beautiful double circular system to cool down print area at 360° wide!

WARNING: ring is at just 4mm from bed, 1mm only from clip, so you must be very strict in print and mount!

As usual in all my design I’ve split all in order to have an easy print of each, and also an easy mounting, with glue, after print!

PS: after the installation of this customization is a good Idea to re-execute the PID Autotest… I’ve do two time, one with fan power off and one with fan power on, and both was really different from the same test executed just couple hours before!

IF YOU “FALL IN LOVE” OF THIS DESIGN, PLEASE, REMEMBER THAT IT TAKE TIME TO BE CREATED, DESIGNED AND SHARED… SO “MAYBE” YOU CAN USE THE “TIP DESIGNED” BUTTON ON MY PROFILE!

Print the circular cooling, the part named “Dual Extruder 3DTouch Radiale – 2 Ring”, is a very complex task! The over tag embedded in this component require a printer fine-tuned with already at least a normal fan cooling system in place, or the internal flow will not be guarantee!
If you do not have any fan cooling in place I kindly suggest you print before the part named “Dual Extruder 3DTouch Radiale – 2 Classic” and install first of all this version.
Assembly interface of both parts, Ring and Classic, is identical right in order to enable use of Classic one to empower the printer before try to print Ring one!

license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
So I took the remix 3 piece done by adibadro and sliced it to a 4 part print. The reason I did this was due to one of the pieces being too tall for my printer to print vertical. I took the longest piece and sliced it to allow all pieces to fit perfectly together. This will allow anyone to print the pieces vertical using a FlashForge Creator and smaller. This will allow you to choose a higher infill and resolution as well
(No supports are needed for this if you are using PLA.)

Printer Brand:

FlashForge

Printer:

Creator Pro

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

1.5

Infill:

30

Notes:

I'm also using the PrininZ Zebra board, so I use no rafts or supports. I just added a little purple glue stick to the bed and use a brim that is 6.0mm away from my print to help prime the extruder.
My temp settings were 225C for the first layer then 215C for the rest. This allowed the PLA to go down smooth and stick better for the first layer. My bed remained at 60C the whole time. After the first layer my cooling fan was set to 100%.
You want that first layer to be perfect so when you glue the pieces together the line will be invisible. I'm writing this and printing at the same time so when I finish I will post pics. So far it looks perfect.

For a multi color egg you can either print each egg one layer at a time, switching filament colors between layers, or print a full egg in each color then mix and match. I printed 6 full eggs in each color then mixed up the layers to create the eggs in the pictures.

Assembly

Assembly will require glue and small lengths of 1.75mm filament. I used cyanoacrylate (super glue) and filament that was left over from spent rolls that were to short for printing.

Assemble the two top layers together (layer 5 and 6) with short lengths of filament. A little bit of super glue is all that is needed, no need to soak it. Assemble the bottom two layers the same way (layer 0 and 1). Next assemble the middle three layers with slightly longer pieces of filament and glue. The dots of layer 3 have two different types, 4 holes are deeper then the others. Dry fit these to ensure they are nice and flush before glueing. Finally glue the layer assemblies together.

Unfortunately it is not as easy to assemble as I would have liked, maybe a future design will be snap together so I will not glue my fingers together again.

description.text:
The electric vehicle owners at the company where I work have figured out over several years, how to fairly share the charging stations at the company. Due to the large number of EVs wanting to charge, and the limited stations, each car is limited to 2 hours. This "deli card" system was worked out over time so that everyone can fairly share and can maximize the use of the charge stations. The laminated paper deli cards don't last very long, so I made these smaller plastic cards. There is one for each hour from 0500 to 2000. They fit into a shirt pocket, and have a hole for hanging on a wire at the charge station. I'm going to work on making a 2 layer version that does not need the support rods and could be printed on a 2 color 2 head printer.

How the "deli card" system works at my work place.

  1. Its ad-hoc, so when you arrive at work in the morning, you grab 2 cards for the 2 hours you want to charge. Example 1000 and 1100
  2. There are 2 parking spots for each charge station. By having 2 parking spots for each charge station, the charge station is in continuous use, without having to have each car owner be there exactly at the hand-off time.This is works very good for public and work charging locations
  3. You pull in at your starting charge time (example 1000) and unplug the car charging, and plug your car in.
  4. The car that was previously charging has an hour to move their car and make space for the next car. They return their cards to the hook or bin at the charge station.
  5. At (this example) 1200 the next car will pull in and move the charge cord from your car to their car.
    Number 4 repeats : You have an hour (1200-1300) to move your car and make space for the next car. You return the (example 1000 and 1100) deli cards to the hook or bin at the charge station.
  6. And so on, this repeats all day long, and starts over on the next day.

This set is public in Tinkercad, so you can customize them for your charge stations.
How to modify: 1. make a duplicate copy. 2. rename it. 3. tinker it. 4. Click the card, un-group 5. click on the 4 support rods for the B the 4 and move them up and off the object, 6. Click the card and un-group. 7. click on the B3-4 and edit it to say what what you want to match your local charge station. 8. Make copies, and move the support rods into place for letters/numbers with centers (like A, B, D, O, P, Q R, 4, 6, 8, 9, 0) 9. click on the text and the hole and the card and GROUP. 9. Click on the support rods and the card and GROUP. 10 exit, move on to the next hour card and repeat.

title: Single E3D V6 Mount with Active Cooling (CTC/Makerbot/FlashForge)

description.text:
Built for the CTC Dual (Converted to Single), but should work on Makerbots and Flashforges.

After heavily modifying everything about my CTC Bizer (Makerbot Replicator clone) printer, it was a real workhorse. However the extruder began to jam frequently, to the point it could not finish a print. I also got rid of the second extruder as I rarely use it (Literally just disconnect the left extruders motor, thermocouple and heating element cables and change the CTCs settings to single extruder).

There are other designs on Thingiverse for an E3D mount on a CTC but none featured active cooling. I wanted to design something from scratch that allowed me to use a silent 40mm fan for the E3D aswell as active cooling. All inside a small package as other designs protrude and smack into the enclosure doors. The active cooling is split well and perfectly positioned so that my hotend doesn't cool down and cool the print just right. My previous experiences with other designs applied too much cooling to one side and caused warping. It's also far away enough from the hotend not to melt. I now use this for ABS and is better than any solution I've tried on Thingiverse (And I've tried loads).

I've designed it using natural shapes for ease of printing and strength. It should print easily and requires a minimal amount of different screws. I've also designed it to be relatively modular as I plan to redesign the cable guide to create a cable chain version.

You HAVE to print frame.stl and e3d-mount.stl but the rest is optional. I highly recommend the entire set over just the frame and mount though.

You will need:
1 x Bowden E3D V6/V6Lite (Metal only, you can reuse the heater block and thermocouple)
12 x M3 x 16mm Countersunk
2 x M3 x 40mm Socket Cap (The long black screws from the CTCs extruder/fan is perfect)
14 x M3 Nuts
2 x 40mm Fans

The fan for the E3D is a 12V silent fan, which is powered by an addiontal 12V rail I added by wiring an AC-DC step down transformer. 24V fans can be wired straight into the power supply. The active cooling fan is a 24V fan scavenged from the printer.

After printing you may need to give some areas a light sanding and the holes a small drill through using a 2.5/3mm bit. If you can't get the head of the screws down a cavity, carefully use a 6.5mm drill the clear it.

Then install all the push to fit nuts. I do this by putting an appropriate sized M3 screw in and fully tighten so the nut gets pulled into the M3 shaped gap. Then remove the screws. For the 2 long screws, I mounted the nut using a M3 x 50mm screw, the nuts for the fans were done with a M3 x 10mm screw.

Start by installing the fans first, I couldn't actually fit the bottom two nuts on the E3D mount, however its no big deal and still works perfectly. I think if printed with active cooling it will fit. Then screw together the frame and E3D mount with the E3D mounted inside (Screws accessible THROUGH the fan). Then attach the entire active cooling part already assembled, and tighten against the frame.

Now sort out the wiring, I've made small grooves towards the bottom of the frame to route the hotend cables. Zip tie together on the cable guide. I have the heater cartridge routed to the left and the thermocouple routed to the right.

Then screw directly into the already existing X-axis carriage mount.

Enjoy!

description.text:
This is my remix of the P3Steel X and Z axis parts that originally came with my with my printer.
The main goal is to eliminate z-wobble effect that I was suffering after 7~8mm of printing height.
The printing quality is now insanely better.
This is what I changed:

  • Fixed the Z threaded rod position based on irobri's cad files
  • Added anti wobbling nuts based on toolson's anti-wobble system
  • Added bottom holding locks to keep the 8mm smooth rods in place (keeping them from skipping out due to hole tolerance)
  • Added top 625ZZ bearing support to threaded rod to limit wobbling effect
  • Replaced tensor printed bearings by a tensor that accepts a couple of F604ZZ improving gt2 belt straightness

WARNING

During print the noise is almost the same.

description.header: How to Generate Custom STL Files
description.text:
Thingiverse Customizer
  • Under "Things Apps Enabled" click on "Open in Customizer".
  • Modify the parameters as you like to customize your cross and base.
  • When everything looks good click on "General Parameters" and change the "Object" to "Cross".
  • Click on "Create Thing" to create the .STL for the cross.
  • Under "General Parameters" change the "Object" to "Base".
  • Click on "Create Thing" to create the .STL for the base.

If you would like to build this as one piece:

  • Under "General Parameters" change the "Object" to "Both".
  • Click on "Create Thing" to create the .STL for the cross and base combination.
  • Hint: To print as one piece without supports change the "Offset" under "Cross Parameters" to 0.

Printer: Printrbot Simple Metal

Rafts: Not required.
Supports: Not required.
Bed Adhesion: Brim - 4mm
Resolution: Normal - .2mm
Infill: 20%
Wall Thickness: 1.2mm
Printing Temperature: 195°C
Bed Temperature: n/a - Heater Bed Not Installed (Yet!)
Retraction: Enabled

Print Speed:

  • Cross: 100mm/sec print speed
  • Base: 60mm/sec for better detail and to minimize printing artifacts

Notes:

  • Printed in PLA:
  • I suggest using a heated bed and brim if you are going to print in ABS as the model has a base geometry that will be inclined to warp.

Ensure your 3D Printer is properly calibrated or you may have issues with the text printing clearly. Also, ensure you have great bed adhesion as both prints have long straight pieces that will be prone to warping. Don't ask how I know. ;)

description.text:
To connect two aluminum extrusions at 90 degrees, you'd need to tap the center hole in one of them and drill a tool hole in the side of the other. But drilling an accurate hole in a little groove is not that easy without a jig. Here's one I made one evening.

This drilling jug uses standard metric nuts as drill guides (because it's far too easy to destroy pure plastic jig with a drill). Nuts will probably get mangled in the process too, but they're far more robust than plastic.

Obviously enough, the nut size you'll need is the same size you're drilling a hole for.
For 2020 (20mm) aluminum extrusion you will need a M5 nut (4.2mm drill bit).
For 1515 (15mm) you will need M4 (3.3mm drill bit).

Put a nut in the slot, slide the jig on the end of the aluminum extrusion and drill away. Very easy.

For yanks with metric deficiency: go buy some metric fasteners, for frogs' snakes!

Prints without any supports if you flip it so the round hole is on the floor.

License is BY CC-SA, meaning you can copy this in your projects, even in the ones you are going to make money on (or if you are a company), but you have to refer to the original design when you do so and provide the sources for your thingy (not the whole product, just this part), even if you modify it. Also, license you're giving it at should be compatible with BY CC-SA. You can google for if yours is compatible.

Sources in this case would be the STL files I've provided on this page and/or the OnShape public project by Toxuin (me), if you'll manage to find it.

title: Tevo Tarantula Z Axis Stabilization Bracket

description.text:
This is a stabilization bracket for the Tevo Tarantula printer. In the stock printer the Z-Axis 'floats' on the flexible shaft coupling which creates some vibrations and compromises rigidity.

To install this you need 1) a standard 8x22x7 bearing and 2) some sort of 8mm shaft collar and 3) 2 x 4mm T-nuts and M4 bolts, which you should already have. The bearing and collar are available for cheap on Amazon. I made my shaft collar on my lathe but you can as well print your own using pretty much any material, see http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:400921

Sample Amazon listings:

https://www.amazon.com/Skateboard-Bearings-Double-Shielded-Silver/dp/B002BBGTK6
https://www.amazon.com/Ruland-MSP-8-SS-Two-Piece-Clamping-Stainless/dp/B0063L7GZW

I did print this bracket with 100% infill for maximum rigidity.

I recommend to place a 8mm washer (or something close to that) between bearing and collar so that the collar does not rub on the shielding of the bearing. In my case the shielding of the bearing was not flush with the inner race of the bearing but YMMV.

UPDATED - August 2017
Based on feedback from the community, I've finally updated this cooler model - Better internal airflow guides, directional rectangular holes. Hope this one works out a little better - thanks to everyone who has contacted me and given me ideas!

The FLSUN Delta's "new effector" - an injection moulded part with a centrifugal part cooler fan comes with a duct that sends cooling air to just one side of the part. I wanted to increase the spread of the cooling - but didn't want a "ring style".

I've gone for a "horseshoe" design that will provide a more even spread but leave visibility around the nozzle. Mounting is via one of the original scrws, plus a shorter M3 screw (you need to have it sticking out only about 1mm) that fits into the "keyhole" slot. I cut down one screw, but you could possibly drill out the hole a little deeper, or buy a smaller screw.

The earlier version with the "nub" attaches with only one of the two original screws, if more stability is required, a small amount of double sided tape can be used on the flat part (I havent needed it)

This is a work in progress design and you should expect updates - Happy for comments to improve this design further.

A friend of mine asked me if I could do a statue of Big Al, the Alabama Crimson Tide mascot. Well, no. I am not well versed in organic modeling. And I couldn't find a pre-made file of Big Al, either. The other model incorporates the plaque with the elephant for a more three-dimensional effect. After looking at it more, I decided that the elephant was too small, so I have added another version with a larger elephant.

A 3-D rendering of an umbilic torus. The design starts in Sage, export to X3D (resulting file included), then import X3D into Blender. In Blender, edit to remove artifacts Sage leaves behind, like a cube of lines around the figure. Now export to STL, then import STL into Cura. In Cura, scale (because graph units in Sage become millimeters in Cura) and situate figure on print platform, then export STL again to form the STL thing file here.

Here is the Sage code to generate the figure:

u, v = var('u, v')
parametric_plot3d([sin(u)*(7+cos(u/3-2*v)+2*cos(u/3+v)), sin(u/3-2*v)+2*sin(u/3+v), cos(u)*(7+cos(u/3-2*v)+2*cos(u/3+v))], (u,-pi,pi), (v,-pi,pi), aspect_ratio=1)

Since Sage is Python-based, be sure to check line breaks. Note that the surface is defined parametrically and plotted using the parametric_plot3d() method. The surface is closed, so Cura already recognizes the STL as representing a solid, without any need to "thicken" the surface in Blender.

description.text:
UPDATE: 18 April 2017:
I should add in a caveat: This design is eventually to be used on a 1.8m wingspan aircraft.

The v21 idea won't work. A single line thickness for internal spars is way too flimsy. Next design to come shortly.

I wanted to test modeling up some RC plane wings in a similar fashion that 3DLabPrint designs theirs, only better. I wanted to design them in such a way that it didn't require expensive slicing software, or very odd slicer settings.

I think a single layer wing skin thickness is just too fragile. 3DLabPrint seems to use a single perimeter for wing skin and 2 perimeters for internal support. I'm testing to see if 2 wing skins and a single for internal support nets a better performing wing. Yes, it will probably weigh more, but by how much?

The v4 file has double perimeters on both the wing skins and internal structure. Also, the internal spars are purely straight, no deviation.

The v21 file has internal spars that lay across one another. I don't feel curved spars really do anything but add aesthetics.

More files/tests to come!

description.text:
This is the 6th major revision and 2nd minor revision of the lamellar armor plates I've been designing for my micronation, Theodia.

The thing that's cool about this lamella design, is that, when assembled, no cords are exposed, meaning the armor should hold up much longer against sharp weaponry. I personally recommend fabricating this the conventional way with UHMW, since it's armor and doing that will get you some decent bullet-resistance; but it's still cool to be able to just print it. Like, printing out body armor: how cool is that?

It's also my first 3D model ever (if you exclude the one we did in game programming class (we were just following a tutorial) or the sphere I made a decade ago in some unnamed 3D editor), and so has a few too many vertices. I'm still getting used to Blender. But starting it in Inkscape helped a lot.
